You&#39;re confusing the url/path part with the name of the route. Change your code to

    @if(Request::path() === &#39;search&#39;)
        &lt;p&gt; results page &lt;/p&gt;
    @else
         &lt;p&gt; Other page &lt;/p&gt;
    @endif

and everything should work as expected. 

From the [documentation](https://laravel.com/docs/5.2/requests#basic-request-information): 

&gt; &quot;_The path method returns the request&#39;s URI._&quot;

The URI part of your route is &quot;`/search`&quot; (which could also be written as `search`). The _name_ of that route is &quot;`results`&quot; which is used to reference that URI: `return route(&#39;results&#39;);` will output &quot;http://localhost:8000/search&quot;

Edit: Routes with parameters:

If you have a route

    Route::get(&#39;/user/{uid}&#39;, [
        &#39;uses&#39; =&gt; &#39;UserController@show&#39;,
        &#39;as&#39; =&gt; &#39;userprofile&#39;
    ]);

you can check for a specific user route (`http://localhost/user/3`) using:

    @if ( Request::path() == &#39;user/3&#39;)
    &lt;p&gt;User Profile 3&lt;/p&gt;
    @else
    &lt;p&gt;NOT User Profile 3&lt;/p&gt;
    @endif

If you want to check any user route (`http://localhost/user/1`, `http://localhost/user/2` ...) use the _name_ of the route:

    @if ( Request::route()-&gt;getName() == &#39;userprofile&#39;)
    &lt;p&gt;User Profile&lt;/p&gt;
    @else
    &lt;p&gt;NOT User Profile&lt;/p&gt;
